I find this very cool, since what I'd heard before seeing this paper was that evidence for this link was mixed. I think the fact that they specifically focus on problematic usage, instead of just hours per day, is what may have contributed to this difference?

Meta-analyses are also often very sensitive to the choices that analysts make when including or excluding individual studies:https://t.co/oZDuD3MpQrLuckily, this paper is very transparent in reporting the systematic methodology they used, and it does seem reasonable!

These results are aggregated from 41 studies, which together surveyed ~40,000 children and youth.That's a lot of data, but there's a lot of noise in this process, since each study can use different thresholds to define problematic use or the mental health outcomes of interest.

But it's impossible to tease apart causality - are the associated mental health differences causing more smartphone use? Is it the other way around? All that can  be said is that they co-occur: "reverse causality cannot be excluded as rationale for the associations found."

And they find that children and young people with problematic smartphone usage are roughly 3x as likely to also be depressed, 3x as likely to be anxious, 3x as likely to have poor sleep, and 2x as likely to have higher perceived stress.

They define problematic smartphone usage (PSU) as "smart phone use associated with at least some element of dysfunctional use, such as anxiety when the phone was not available, or neglect of other activities" and estimate that ~1/4 of the population under 25 meets this criteria.

I'm not very good at evaluating the quality of meta-analyses, but this study of the prevalence of problematic smartphone usage and associated mental health issues seems to show an extremely strong relationship!https://t.co/vJiKFvaJZD

The dismantling of the NHS has exacerbated the structural inequality that leads to the poor treatment of trans* and disabled people. I do NOT blame the doctors/nurses. I blame the lack of trans* awareness training or funding for such. I blame the UK government.

I waited 2 years for a psychology referral. I waited 6 months for a neurology referral. I waited 4 months for a rheumatology referral. I will have been waiting 18 months for my gender identity clinic referral.  Austerity has destroyed the NHS. 9/

I have no doubt that both my mental health diagnosis and my gender identity have been barriers to decent medical care. Consciously or not, healthcare professionals (and in some cases, others) have not taken the very real pain and clinical signs I am experiencing seriously. 8/

Then, this year, when the symptoms had made it nearly impossible to function, I frustatedly went back to the GP insisting there must be something autoimmune going on... He scrolled up my notes and told me the ANA was indeed positive. 7/

Because of my access to scientific literature (which most people, wrongfully, do not get), I hypothesised years ago that my symptoms were autoimmune in nature. I requested to have an anti-nuclear antibody (ANA) test in 2017, and was told the result  was "unremarkable". 6/

I'm grateful to not have bladder cancer. Obviously. But this experience was one of the worst of my life and it was avoidable. It didnt feel like modern medicine. It felt medieval. I was screaming in agony. I have more tests coming up; my diagnosis is looking like autoimmunity. 5/

Because of my tension, my fear and the uncontrollable jerking of my body from sobbing so much (partly from the pain and partly from the nurses holding me down and saying "calm down, SIR") the cytoscope damaged me and I am now in even more pain than before. 4/

As soon as I entered the theatre the surgeon called me "sir", despite having supposedly read my file which clearly states my identity and pronoun preferences, and my referral to the gender identity clinic. I corrected him and he ignored it 3/

was told I could be sedated for the procedure because I was incredibly anxious about it and in an immense amount of pain. I told the person on the phone when the appointment was made and he said he would talk to the nurses. I got to the appointment and no sedation was offered. 2/

I had a traumatic experience with the NHS on monday and I've been wondering whether or not to share about it but I think it has to be said especially with the election coming up. I have had very scary symptoms for the last year which culminated in the need for a cytoscopy. 1/

Can LibDems or Labour get that trust in the next 2 weeks? Will tactical voting on the 'Remain' ticket override other concerns? Will Boris Johnson make a big enough gaffe to lose trust? I don't know, but it's pretty depressing being a UK voter at the moment.
(and even if you believe any of the above, to get people to change their mind doesn't start from any of these positions)

I caution in just saying these people are stupid (they are not) or chronically mislead (Facebook placed ads aren't that good) or bigots/racist (UK has it's fair proportion of racists; they will vote Tory or BXP, but that's a minority of these voters in my view).

I get people might think this is unfair; that the Tories play dirty (too dirty? dirtier than Labour and LibDems?), and that this all too cynical, but in my view this is not grasping the central issue that they are not making the emotional connection right.

This loss of trust is why I think polls are so Tory at the moment; the other options are not connecting emotionally to a big chunk of the UK (mainly England, but also a big part of Wales, bits of Scotland; Northern Ireland is its own political universe).

It often comes across that anyone who voted for the Tories over the last 40 years will have to publicly recant their position before being welcomed into this Labour party; to vote Labour is to say everything has gone to the dogs for the last 40 years.

Furthermore, many people feel I think feel the current Labour front bench care far more for an international left wing project, reminiscent of the 1970s/early 80s, than the people who live in the UK. Labour seems as motivated by things outside of the UK as inside.

tl;dr what if every time you submit a paper, you commit to providing a review too?If you're behind on reviewing others, no submissions for you! https://t.co/c6l0LXeuDk

The problem is "will people then just provide low-quality reviews?"Well, (1) they already do and (2) if reviews have some value, this makes it easier for editors to "reject reviews"Individuals in bad standing would not be allowed to submit new papers

My alternative: each submission (whether accepted or not) carries a commitment to provide a review in the futureIt limits over-submission to journals where the paper is almost certain to be rejected, it is not a pure dead-weight lossAlso, makes it easier to get reviewers

The obvious alternative is a monetary tax: submissions cost $100. It would be more efficient than the current system, but it would still have problems (not least of which is that $100 is not a lot in Norway, but it's a huge deal elsewhere)

Contra @ATabarrok, I don't think formatting requirements are pointless (https://t.co/EnbsjlKQaS), they are a tax on submission as journals are already inundated with submissionsThe real issue is that it is a very inefficient tax as it's pure waste

I'll be in Boston until the end of the year, and then working part-time in Sydney and Melbourne from January until the Centre formally launches in May. Looking forward to getting started!

Special thanks to @Jalfoldi for her tireless work on gnomAD and many other projects, and to @HeidiRehm and @dalygene for their incredible support over the years, as well as their willingness to take on even more work to ensure the team can continue to thrive after I leave.

Enormous thanks to so many people - my lab members, past and present, a remarkable set of human beings; the senior staff who've kept the ship on track; our many collaborators; and the men and women of the @broadgenomics and Data Sciences Platforms.

And the Center for Mendelian Genomics and Rare Genomes Project will keep sequencing thousands of rare disease families each year, under the leadership of @HeidiRehm and @AnneOtation - and I'll stay involved in developing and applying new methods for rare disease diagnosis.

Fortunately the work we've done in Boston will continue. gnomAD will keep getting bigger and better, and doing new science, with @HeidiRehm and @dalygene as co-directors, and a steering council including me, @bmneale, @TalkowskiLab, @AnneOtation, Grace Tiao and @mattsolomonson.

This decision is bittersweet. I couldn't have asked for a better home than @broadinstitute and MGH over the last 7 years, and couldn't be prouder of the things my team has achieved. But Australia is where my family and heart is, as well as some amazing scientific opportunities.

We'll be formally launching in May 2020. We're recruiting computational biologists, statistical geneticists, software engineers, trainees, and much more. Job ads are coming soon, but if you're keen on doing population-scale genomics in Sydney or Melbourne, DM me.

The Centre will build the tools and resources needed to implement population-scale genomic medicine in Australia, a country of 25 million people with a universal healthcare system, rich ancestral diversity, and a vibrant and collaborative human genomics community.

I'll be directing a new centre for population genomics as a partnership between the Garvan Institute of Medical Research in Sydney and the Murdoch Children's Research Institute in Melbourne, bridging two world-class research institutes in the two largest cities in the country.
After seven amazing years in Boston, I am both sad and excited to (finally) be able to officially announce that I'll be returning to my native Australia in 2020 to start a new adventure!

the solution: 1. build a neighbour joining tree (or any cluster)2. get 10-15 representative individuals, for example using Treemer3. Use those 10-15 for the model instead, no need to calculate billions of combinations

I 'solved' this by using, for each step, 5000 random combinations instead of all possible combinations - with low-diversity datasets that works fine. but I have a dataset with diverse individuals, so the resulting model would be inaccurate as rare combos wouldn't show up!

Here it is: I was trying to make a model like https://t.co/Ks8OYJVWrg, which requires all possible combinations for 2, 3, 4, .... n individuals With 9 individuals that's not particularly much, but with 80 that's billions and billions of combinations

Note that this is only BAM with default superFreq, nothing else. The original paper used a combination of 8 methods, including manual variant filters/consensus calls to produce similar output. And still (imo) didn't capture the role of the CNAs very well.

The information is still there, but needs a bit more curation to dig out, and we need to rely more on variant annotation (superFreq annotates and highlights with COSMIC and ClinVar) to find the driver mutations without a matched normal. Sample-specific clones more reliable.

We also see a large number of new variants tracked: rare germline variants. And two cases have new false clones. This is a recurring pattern with analysis without matched normal: good recall, but with significant added noise.
(The CNAs are still called, but with increased uncertainty without matched normal, so some do not meet the cuts to be included in the clonal tracking stage.)

These form the black germline clone. Relapse and diagnosis specific variants separate from that clone, but early somatic variants may get eaten if all samples are pure (these are sorted cells, so very pure). All AML point mutations are retained, but some CNAs are not tracked. https://t.co/2Udc1y5Qrz

We then remove the matched normal from the analysis and run again. SuperFreq filters common germline variants, but anything below 0.1% population frequency (dbSNP/ExAC) is tracked as somatic. Variants consistent with 100% clonality in all samples are classified as germline like.

My favourite here is the chr8 AAB/ABB CNA call in AML.102! üòÅ Both diagnosis and relapse have gain of chr8, but superFreq finds that the gains are of different alleles, so must be different events, and automatically splits into two events that are placed into different clones! https://t.co/ALeyQrwiyq

Another point is that superFreq tracks CNAs, which sometimes match up with high VAF of covered variants in the same clone (AML.084 and AML.110). Very strong and common indication of a driver mutation, that isn't usually tracked by similar pipelines.

Lots of things to take in here. First takeaway is probably that we see clear early clones, diagnosis specific clones and relapse specific clones, and we see common AML drivers tracked and annotated. The point mutations in AML genes match the original papers calls.

On to end-to-end analysis. It's common to use SNP-arrays as hard truth for exome CNA callers. While that probably would be exaggerating the quality of ASCAT calls a bit, I think it's fair to say that superFreq calls fewer but more reliable small CNA segments.

SuperFreq calls way fewer small segments than both ASCAT and Sequenza, but the ones that are called are usually called by ASCAT as well. ASCAT and Sequenza both call many, but mostly different, small segments.

Anyway, I'm just feeling particularly heartbroken. The areas I know and love are reduced to ash. People I know in these areas are afraid and trying to fight to maintain their livelihoods. And all most of us can do, is simply hope for rain.

We've never dealt with this scale of fire disaster. Yes, there's historically been very large and tragic fires, but this many at once? It's hard enough for one area to rebuild after such devastation, how do large numbers of communities across 2 states do it?

I'm just so sad. Seeing national parks reduced to ash, rainforest burn, people lose everything, communities gutted, ecosystems pushed to the brink. Day after day. That knowing the longer it goes on, the harder it gets & there isn't coming back from this.
The horrific thing is that for many communities, recovery won't be happening. There's no infrastructure support, there's no plan, there's no water, there's no money to build again.

I grew up near Esk and Crows Nest. And I've seen fires out there before. But not like this. Not where the break doesn't seem to be coming. Not where it's entire sections of country burning simultaneously.Not where it's 40+ degrees in spring.

Extensions include:- Spatial coordinates can now be supplied to perform higher order testing across physical space!- Function to share permutation rounds among tests for a speed boost
- Any unweighted concordance function can also be used in conjunction with a block shape weighting scheme, e.g. mutual information, distance correlation, interquartile range even!

Generalisation in that:- Any user-defined concordance function can be supplied, with arguments for sample-specific weights, e.g. weighted Pearson/Spearman correlation, weighted zero-inflated Pearson/Spearman, weighted variance/CV, or any other weighted function you like.

This is a generalisation and extension to the approach published last year, Differential Correlation across Ranked Samples (DCARS), where gene-pairs were tested for changes in weighted Spearman correlation across sample rankings.https://t.co/MxFgN6k4Wp

scHOT will then calculate a vector of weighted concordances given the weighting scheme, and test using sample permutations, if this is significantly more variable than you would expect by chance. https://t.co/w2m28il7A2

scHOT requires the following input & params:- Gene expression matrix- Trajectory ordering or spatial coordinates- A set of genes or gene-pairs to test- Weighting scheme shape and span- Weighted concordance function

Our latest preprint describing single cell Higher Order Testing (scHOT). This is a framework for testing changes in higher order statistics (variability or correlation) along a single cell trajectory or across physical space.https://t.co/gcENx91Mra

Combining SAMMSON KD with BRAFi results in tumor regression (with increase in apoptosis). Note: no ASO approved therapy for cancer. I'll not post some details on unpublished work; altogether impressive result by targeting mitochondrial translation.

p32 and CARF interact in a RNA (and SAMMSON) dependent manner. SAMMSON in other systems, by ectopic expression, also increases translation (and drive transformation). A true RNA oncogene. If KD SAMMSON, translation is blocked in the mitochondria only (but not blocking the tumor)

SAMMSON confers growth advantage to melanoma cells in nude mice. Developed a protocol similar to Chirp and captured by mass-spec proteins attached to SAMMSON" p32, XRN2 (and CARF). Role in rRNA biogenesis and ribosome biogenesis.

SAMMSON is a lncRNA that is melanoma specific (90% of patients). SAMMSON is regulated by Sox-10 that. There is a LTR1A2 (a primate specific). SAMMSON is cytoplasmic, sarted to be expressed in the vertical growth phase (when the tumor turns to be malignant).

For tomatoes, next year ill be growing a few of each line I'm stabilizing. The garden won't be the big jungle of random F2s like it was this year.I expect to dedicate more space to dry beans. I'm not sure what target volume would represent a year's worth of beans though.
This year I probably produced enough dried tomatoes & peppers to last through the year. (Powdered tomato is a wonderful ingredient! Add it to soups, sauces, pasta, nachos, pizza, etc.)
I do like the idea of growing all that we'll need for the year of some crop or other, but there's no way I could fully support our food needs with the space/time constraints I have.
If I was growing for maximum production, I would grow fewer varieties and use fertilizers and other garden chemicals to support that productivity.
But seriously, essentially everything I grow is part of some #PlantBreeding project or other. If I wanted potatoes & onions like the ones at the grocer, I'd just get them there.
A friend tonight asked, "How much of your garden is for growing food vs just an extension of your lab?"I mean. Yes.

There goes an hour an a half of my life and my colleague's life! Thanks @golang!
However, this runs re-initialization which binds to a fixed port in the same container, causing the process to fail.

Understandably, @bugsnag, and others like it, want to detect panics anywhere. Because there's no global panic recoverer, they need a workaround. They fork&exec your command and listen to stderr. Clever.

In @golang, panics on any goroutine that aren't recovered cause the process to exit. This means if you call out to *any* library that spawns a goroutine that doesn't recover, your process might crash. There's nothing you can do about it. No global panic recoverer.

We had a container that was crashing due to inexplicably binding to the same port twice. We checked, double-checked, triple-checked that the code couldn't possibly bind to the same port. It was like we were running the same process twice in one container.

@EMBO It remains that every time a publisher makes their accounts public (@eLife @PLOS), we see that scientific publishing is more expensive that "setting up a webpage", and a realistic model to pay for these costs is needed.

@EMBO A risk is that no one would pay for subscription to news & views if research is OA. That would imply that the community doesn't in fact value these pieces, in which case it's logical if they disapear.

@EMBO Second, EMBO includes the cost of "review articles, opinion pieces, editorials and News & Views articles". These could arguably remain on a subscription model, since they are not primary output of publicly-paid research.
